1006
01:43:41,680 --> 01:43:45,890
I'm having that tie... one way or another.

1007
01:44:07,440 --> 01:44:08,851
(CHUCKLES)

1008
01:44:10,840 --> 01:44:12,729
(SCREAMS)

1009
01:44:12,840 --> 01:44:15,684
That's it. That's it.

1010
01:44:16,600 --> 01:44:18,170
(SCREAMS RESONATE)

1011
01:44:19,880 --> 01:44:22,611
LAING: 'Ever thought
of leaving the nest yourself?'

1012
01:44:23,240 --> 01:44:25,766
ROYAL: I was the first to arrive.

1013
01:44:27,240 --> 01:44:29,766
I shall be the last to leave.

1014
01:44:34,120 --> 01:44:36,566
(HELEN CONTINUES SCREAMING)

1015
01:44:36,680 --> 01:44:40,526
You recall us speaking about my hopes

1016
01:44:40,640 --> 01:44:44,770
for the building to be
a crucible for change?

1017
01:44:44,880 --> 01:44:46,291
Of course.

1018
01:44:46,400 --> 01:44:51,440
Well, all this has made me realise
something quite fundamental.

1019
01:44:51,600 --> 01:44:54,843
It wasn't that I left an element out.

1020
01:44:54,960 --> 01:44:57,611
It was that I put too many in.

1021
01:44:59,240 --> 01:45:02,449
And now the building's failure

1022
01:45:02,600 --> 01:45:05,968
has offered those people

1023
01:45:06,080 --> 01:45:10,404
the beginnings of a means
of escape to a new life.

1024
01:45:10,560 --> 01:45:11,971
Hm.

1025
01:45:16,120 --> 01:45:18,282
Who knows?

1026
01:45:18,400 --> 01:45:22,689
Perhaps it will become a paradigm
for future developments.

1027
01:45:22,800 --> 01:45:24,404
(CHUCKLES)

1028
01:45:27,000 --> 01:45:30,129
And you... have you settled?

1029
01:45:31,680 --> 01:45:33,921
I believe so. Mm.

1030
01:45:37,000 --> 01:45:38,684
Impressions?

1031
01:45:45,840 --> 01:45:47,569
(CLEARS THROAT)

1032
01:45:56,640 --> 01:45:59,291
Well, the lights,

1033
01:45:59,400 --> 01:46:03,610
fire like... neurons in a great brain.

1034
01:46:04,360 --> 01:46:07,648
'The lifts seem like
the chambers of a heart.'

1035
01:46:07,760 --> 01:46:09,091
- (SCREAMS)
- Yes!

1036
01:46:09,200 --> 01:46:12,761
- LAING: 'And when I move...
- That's it.

1037
01:46:12,880 --> 01:46:16,123
'...I move along its corridors
like a cell...'

1038
01:46:16,240 --> 01:46:18,129
(LAUGHS)

1039
01:46:18,240 --> 01:46:20,129
'...in a network of arteries.'

1040
01:46:20,240 --> 01:46:22,242
There we are.

1041
01:46:24,360 --> 01:46:27,250
There. That wasn't so bad,
now, was it, huh?

1042
01:46:28,320 --> 01:46:30,288
Bravo.

1043
01:46:30,400 --> 01:46:32,323
(BABY CRIES)

1044
01:46:35,240 --> 01:46:36,765
ROYAL: Hm...

1045
01:46:46,640 --> 01:46:51,089
- What... What is this?
- What do you think?

1046
01:47:01,600 --> 01:47:03,250
Pudding?

1047
01:47:04,840 --> 01:47:07,320
LAING: Right, while I've got your ear...

1048
01:47:08,880 --> 01:47:10,689
about Richard Wilder.

1049
01:47:10,800 --> 01:47:15,249
You don't need to worry
about Richard, or the others.

1050
01:47:28,320 --> 01:47:30,971
WOMAN: Bloody Mary, John?
Wet the baby's head.

1051
01:47:31,080 --> 01:47:33,367
Where are all the menfolk?

1052
01:47:34,400 --> 01:47:37,244
Cosgrove was taken, I'm afraid.

1053
01:47:37,360 --> 01:47:39,522
On his way back from work.

1054
01:47:39,640 --> 01:47:41,802
Christ. Really?

1055
01:47:43,600 --> 01:47:46,683
- Simmons has gone to get him back.
- Oh.

1056
01:47:46,800 --> 01:47:48,882
They may be some time.

1057
01:47:50,400 --> 01:47:53,688
Now, tell me... I can't remember.

1058
01:47:53,800 --> 01:47:57,805
Have I ever given you my autograph?

1059
01:48:24,880 --> 01:48:27,167
Whose area? There's another.

1060
01:48:44,880 --> 01:48:46,962
(MECHANICAL WHIRRING)

1061
01:48:53,240 --> 01:48:54,765
WILDER: Helen!

1062
01:48:55,840 --> 01:48:57,604
Helen!

1063
01:49:00,080 --> 01:49:01,923
Helen!

1064
01:49:05,760 --> 01:49:07,171
It's you.

1065
01:49:10,760 --> 01:49:12,762
- The architect.
- Yes.

1066
01:49:16,080 --> 01:49:18,731
You see, you've made a mistake there.

1067
01:49:18,840 --> 01:49:20,842
If you'd have confessed your sins
on camera

1068
01:49:20,960 --> 01:49:23,281
when our paths crossed in the foyer,

1069
01:49:23,400 --> 01:49:25,926
I'd have probably edited this bit out.

1070
01:49:26,920 --> 01:49:30,242
I'm not accountable to you, Mr Wilder.

1071
01:49:32,160 --> 01:49:35,528
Too late now, anyway. Camera broke.

1072
01:49:35,640 --> 01:49:38,041
Oh, just one thing before you go.

1073
01:49:39,400 --> 01:49:41,926
Why exactly did you take my wife?

1074
01:49:43,400 --> 01:49:48,201
I can assure you, I have no interest
in your personal property.

1075
01:49:48,320 --> 01:49:50,971
Because I ask myself,
why would a great man like you

1076
01:49:51,080 --> 01:49:53,890
feel the need to hide
behind women's skirts?

1077
01:49:54,000 --> 01:49:57,766
Behind children, even.
Your own, as well as others.

1078
01:49:57,880 --> 01:50:01,441
How dare you judge me! How dare...

1079
01:50:01,600 --> 01:50:03,887
- Helen!
- (GUNSHOT)

1080
01:50:10,360 --> 01:50:16,367
That's right. You sit there
and think about what you've done.

1081
01:50:55,600 --> 01:50:58,809
(# "BRANDENBURG CONCERTO NO.4" BY JS BACH)

1082
01:51:10,960 --> 01:51:14,601
LAING: 'On the whole,
life in the high-rise was good.

1083
01:51:16,000 --> 01:51:18,287
'There had been no obvious point
at which it had moved

1084
01:51:18,400 --> 01:51:21,404
'into a clearly more sinister dimension.

1085
01:51:22,800 --> 01:51:24,882
'Helen was right.

1086
01:51:25,000 --> 01:51:27,924
'It was a huge children's party,

1087
01:51:28,040 --> 01:51:30,361
'which had got out of hand.

1088
01:51:31,400 --> 01:51:35,246
'Of course, Laing was sorry
the architect had died.

1089
01:51:35,360 --> 01:51:39,046
'He felt he owed the man
a debt of gratitude for his new family.

1090
01:51:40,400 --> 01:51:44,883
'The first Laing had ever
really felt part of.

1091
01:51:55,040 --> 01:51:59,125
'Now that several potential patients
had emerged here in the building,

1092
01:51:59,240 --> 01:52:01,925
'Laing might start
a private medical practice...'

1093
01:52:02,040 --> 01:52:04,771
STEELE: Do you fancy a drink?
Cosgrove's here.

1094
01:52:04,880 --> 01:52:10,284
LAING: '...and help others surrender
to a logic more powerful than reason.'

1095
01:52:10,400 --> 01:52:13,609
All, uh... boys together.

1096
01:52:15,680 --> 01:52:20,368
Laing's, uh, got someone waiting.
You know how it is.

1097
01:52:21,320 --> 01:52:23,209
Say no more.

1098
01:52:26,400 --> 01:52:29,290
LAING: 'One thing was certain.

1099
01:52:29,400 --> 01:52:32,688
'Now that everything
was getting back to normal,

1100
01:52:32,800 --> 01:52:35,007
'Laing would throw his own party,

1101
01:52:35,120 --> 01:52:40,251
'a modest project which, nevertheless,
required careful and cautious planning.

1102
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:45,004
'For now, he would sit back...

1103
01:52:46,360 --> 01:52:48,966
'...eat the rest of the dog,

1104
01:52:49,080 --> 01:52:51,811
'and wait for failure
to reach the second tower

1105
01:52:51,920 --> 01:52:54,002
'of the high-rise development...

1106
01:52:55,160 --> 01:53:01,361
'...ready to welcome its residents
into this new world... with open arms.'

1107
01:53:08,400 --> 01:53:10,323
I heard you out there.

1108
01:53:12,080 --> 01:53:14,128
Who were you talking to?

1109
01:53:15,240 --> 01:53:16,890
No one.

1110
01:53:18,200 --> 01:53:20,009
Just the building.

1111
01:53:21,640 --> 01:53:23,005
(RADIO BUZZES)

1112
01:53:23,120 --> 01:53:25,202
MARGARET THATCHER:
'A free-enterprise system

1113
01:53:25,320 --> 01:53:28,290
'is a necessary
but not a sufficient condition.

1114
01:53:28,400 --> 01:53:33,042
'There is only one economic system
in the world, and that is capitalism.

1115
01:53:33,160 --> 01:53:35,561
'The difference lies
in whether the capital

1116
01:53:35,680 --> 01:53:39,287
'is in the hands of the state
or whether the greater part of it

1117
01:53:39,400 --> 01:53:43,121
'is in the hands of people
outside of state control.

1118
01:53:43,240 --> 01:53:48,963
'Where there is state capitalism,
there will never be political freedom.'

1119
01:53:49,080 --> 01:53:51,811
(# "INDUSTRIAL ESTATE" BY THE FALL)

